[{"id":39631,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c07bc657-e733-4881-94a6-90e5ed5b9b68-9896822_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 351px; height: 260px;\" /></p><p>Potential distribution at each point in the circuit is shown in above diagram.</p><p>Since, both&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math>&nbsp;resistors&nbsp;are maintained at same potential difference, so current will be same, thus, using Ohm&#39;s law,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Now, current&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Hence, the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced open=\"|\" close=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39842,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50296732-3148-45b7-a21b-aa18ff8e93c4-image.png\" style=\"width: 296px; height: 184px;\" /><br /><br />Assuming potential at B = 0, then w.r.t. B the potential of other points are as shown in figure then<br /><br />So, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>D</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>D</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39606,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/55560a8f-5c72-4b07-a1d3-7cd4c51763be.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 205px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d4ac53ce-104f-434c-a6ce-916176c31ffe.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 199px;\" /></p><p>In the first circuit diagram, the diodes&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;are forward biased and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>D</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is reverse biased(Hence, no current through it). So the circuit is simplified to the second diagram.</p><p>Hence, the equivalent resistance is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>20</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p>Using Ohm&#39;s law, the current is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>20</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>30</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39536,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Wheatstone bridge with P = 1Ω, Q = 2Ω, R = 2Ω, S = 4Ω<br>$\\frac{P}{Q} = \\frac{R}{S} = \\frac{1}{2}$ → Bridge is balanced, no current through middle 1Ω.<br>$R_{AB}$: Upper (3Ω) and Lower (6Ω) in parallel = $\\frac{3 \\times 6}{9} = 2Ω$<br>Total resistance = 1 + 2 = 3Ω<br>Current $I = \\frac{9}{3} = 3$ A<br>Power between A and B: $P = I^2 R_{AB} = 9 \\times 2 = 18$ W<br>Heat in 1 min = $18 \\times 60 = 1080$ J","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39771,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math><mn>25</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math><mn>15</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math><mn>20</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Total power is <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>4325</mn><mi></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math><br />So current <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4325</mn><mn>220</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>66</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>so we have to use a fuse which can tolerate atleast 20 A current.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39829,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1600&nbsp;</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>100&nbsp;</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>200&nbsp;</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>400&nbsp;</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mfrac><mi>l</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi>A</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>V</mi></math><br /><math><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> constant<br /><math><mi>V</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> constant<br /><math><mi>R</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1600&#160;</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39862,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["Statement-<math><mrow><mo>I</mo> </mrow> </math> is true, Statement-<math><mrow><mo>II</mo> </mrow> </math> is false.","Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>I</mo> </mrow> </math> is false, Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>II</mo> </mrow> </math> is true.","Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>I</mo> </mrow> </math> is true, Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>II</mo> </mrow> </math> is true, Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>II</mo> </mrow> </math> is the correct explanation of Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>I</mo> </mrow> </math>.","Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>I</mo> </mrow> </math> is true, Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>II</mo> </mrow> </math> is true, Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>II</mo> </mrow> </math> is not the correct explanation of Statement-<math> <mrow> <mo>I</mo> </mrow> </math>."],"answer":1,"solution":"For higher range resistance should be less,so statement I is false.<br /><br />To increase the range by n-times additional shunt should be placed&nbsp;<math><mi>S</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac></math> where 'G' resistance of galvanometer","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39521,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Using Kirchhoff's laws on the bridge circuit with resistances $6\\Omega, 3\\Omega, 3\\Omega, 3\\Omega, 6\\Omega$ and applying a 1V test voltage:<br><br>From the loop equation:<br>$6i_1 + 3(2i_1 - i) = 3(i - i_1)$<br><br>$15i_1 = 6i \\Rightarrow i_1 = \\frac{2}{5}i$ ...(1)<br><br>From the second loop:<br>$3(i - i_1) + 6i_1 = 1$<br>$3i + 3i_1 = 1$<br><br>$\\left(3 + \\frac{6}{5}\\right)i = 1$<br><br>$i = \\frac{5}{21}$ A $= \\frac{1V}{R_{eq}}$<br><br>$R_{eq} = \\frac{21}{5} = 4.2 \\ \\Omega$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39844,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" height=\"111\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image6-ffa0c0fc-5747-4508-9d87-43a6c5314563.jpg\" width=\"228\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image7-250e70ee-f021-41d2-a076-abd81c4bb66f.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image8-9bc489d6-80e5-4d95-9dac-ec111e2e9122.jpg\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image9-f4f0a304-2cb8-472b-afbc-c23128e847db.jpg\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"We know that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>d</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>k</mi><msqrt><mi>E</mi></msqrt></math> and <math><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></msub></math>,&nbsp;<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>k</mi><msqrt><mi>E</mi></msqrt></math><math><mo>&#8757;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>d</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>d</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msqrt><mi>V</mi></msqrt><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>V</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. So,&nbsp;<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/image10-eedf94a2-b699-4c22-86cf-832174e20bb4.jpg\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39600,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo> </mo><mi>μA</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>120</mn><mo> </mo><mi>μA</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>60</mn><mo> </mo><mi>μA</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>180</mn><mo> </mo><mi>μA</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In a moving coil galvanometer, the current is related to the angle of deflection by the formula:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>∝</mo><mi>θ</mi><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>From equation (1), it follow sthat<br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>θ</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>θ</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mrow><mn>200</mn><mo> </mo><mi>μA</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>10</mn></mfrac></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>3</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>10</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo> </mo><mi>μA</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39902,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$0.03 \\Omega$","$0.3 \\Omega$","$0.9 \\Omega$","$0.09 \\Omega$"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":39907,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["1","4","2","3"],"answer":1,"solution":"$P_1=V^2 / R ; P_2=\\frac{V^2}{(R / 2)}+\\frac{V^2}{(R / 2)}=4 \\frac{V^2}{R}=4 P_1$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":39574,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & i=K \\theta \\\\ & \\frac{2}{G+R}=K \\theta \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{\\theta}=\\frac{(G+R) K}{2}=R\\left(\\frac{K}{2}\\right)+\\frac{K G}{2} \\\\ & \\text { Slope }=\\frac{K}{2}=\\frac{1}{4} \\Rightarrow K=0.5=5 \\times 10^{-1} A\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39563,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{R}_{\\text {heater }}=\\frac{\\mathrm{V}^2}{\\mathrm{P}}=\\frac{(100)^2}{1000}=10 \\Omega$\nFor heater $P=\\frac{V^2}{R} \\Rightarrow V=\\sqrt{P R}$\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{V}=\\sqrt{62.5 \\times 10} \\\\ & \\mathrm{~V}=25 \\mathrm{v}\\end{aligned}$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/jCh-MxWtyOYIAtR1RVsjZDkHaxZyIV_RGyJ1Y8euXyo.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & i_1=\\frac{75}{10}=7.5 \\mathrm{~A}, \\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{H}}=\\frac{25}{10}=2.5 \\mathrm{~A} . \\\\ & \\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{R}}=\\mathrm{i}_1-\\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{H}}=5 \\\\ & \\mathrm{~V}=\\mathrm{IR} \\\\ & \\mathrm{R}=\\frac{25}{5}=5 \\Omega\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39649,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e22dc111-e69c-4bea-a268-14d7d5011a56-9894227.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 195px;\" /></p><p>In the given circuit, both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math> resistors&nbsp;get&nbsp;shorted out, thus no current will flow from them. Removing the resistors from which no current will flow.</p><p>Now, the circuit can be redrawn as shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7c2a49c7-822c-41f6-b1fd-e2dd0fd9a8f1-9894227_2.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 200px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>eq</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#8214;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>eq</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>eq</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39851,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["Circuit A with $\\mathrm{G}=\\frac{\\mathrm{RS}}{(\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{S})}$","Circuit B with $\\mathrm{G}=\\mathrm{S}$","Circuit $\\mathrm{C}$ with $\\mathrm{G}=\\mathrm{S}$","Circuit $D$ with $\\left.G=\\frac{R S}{(R-S}\\right)$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The correct circuit diagram is $D$ with galvanometer resistance\n$$\nG=\\frac{R S}{R-S}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39537,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["16","14","10","12"],"answer":3,"solution":"As $r=\\frac{R}{6}$<br/><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7ugV3KH7Irs6GVJ4RACoUGQTmHQ_MQfXG5dAG1Pr2m4.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>(As balanced wheat stone bridge is formed) Now, Equivalent resistance between A and B can be written as<br/>$\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{AB}}}=\\frac{1}{2 \\mathrm{r}}+\\frac{1}{2 \\mathrm{r}}+\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{r}}=\\frac{2}{\\mathrm{r}}$<br/>$\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{AB}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{12}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39861,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.3</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>zero</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.9</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Resistance of bulb,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msub><mi>P</mi><mi>b</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>120</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>120</mn></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>240</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math><br />Resistance of heater,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>h</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msub><mi>P</mi><mi>h</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>120</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>120</mn></mrow><mn>240</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6c6faa30-134a-4aff-8c54-19863d714a31-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 209px;\" /></p><p>Voltage across bulb before the&nbsp;heater is not connected,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>b</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>b</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>120</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>240</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mn>246</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>117</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>07</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>Now the bulb and heater are connected in parallel.</p><p>Resistance of the combination is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>240</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>240</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>60</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>48</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math><br />Voltage across bulb after the heater is switched on,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>120</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>48</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>48</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>106</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>66</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>The decrease in the voltage is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>117</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>07</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>106</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>66</mn><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p>Note: Here supply voltage is taken as rated voltage.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39908,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["expand","compress","insulator","none of these"],"answer":1,"solution":"It will compress due to the force of attraction between two adjacent coils carrying current in the same direction","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":39889,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["equal to the resistance of the load.","very large as compared to the load resistance.","zero.","non-zero but less than the resistance of the load."],"answer":1,"solution":"$I=\\frac{E_0}{R+r} \\square \\frac{E}{r}$ if $R < r$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":39766,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math><mn>0.4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","zero"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/68a4832a-3931-4448-b7a3-961ffa664150-image.png\" /><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math><br /><math><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>A</mi></math><br /><math><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>A</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39590,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cafbf6da-e5ec-482e-a2ed-50d4bf93dc50.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 215px;\"/></p><p>Voltage across <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>200</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>.</p><p>Therefore, current through the battery, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>200</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Now, equivalent resistance of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo> </mo><mo>&amp;</mo><mo> </mo><mn>100</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math>,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>For voltmeter, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>200</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>200</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>200</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39588,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f42eabea-9ddf-496a-9e64-8a5e02364f07.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 145px;\"/></p><p>In the above diagram, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mi>Ω</mi></math> is short circuit. Therefore, we can remove it.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e556acc9-5b5c-4f32-8b31-cb0b4a29c5cf.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 136px;\"/></p><p>In the left part, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math> are in parallel combination, which will give us <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math> which again in turn is in series combination with the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math>(adjacent to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math> resistor), therefore net contribution of this part will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math>. </p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c3d12626-fa50-4fec-8be6-30cf01ba5014.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 148px;\"/></p><p>Now, all three <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math> are in parallel across point A &amp; B, therefore <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>Ω</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39827,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math><mn>2.5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>1.5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&nbsp;Ω</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Without shunting conditions,&nbsp;<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7fbea868-8f3b-4191-9c13-cc9f92f28cf7-image.png\" style=\"width: 249px; height: 191px;\" /><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>52</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></math>, when, balanced, where, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo></math> potential gradient of wire, with shunting condition<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2bdbc8c8-0a1a-4f11-8e93-dc5cc6424f52-image.png\" style=\"width: 246px; height: 259px;\" /><br /><br />On balancing,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>E</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.<br />On solving:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>52</mn><mn>40</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1.5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39650,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>80</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/600606ec-53ad-4fa1-a1b1-a67242e2a4ce-52d8e4b6-8788-47af-a2c6-6e89ec097a11-9894021.PNG\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 198px;\" /></p><p>As we know,&nbsp;voltmeter is connected in parallel to the element being measured.</p><p>The equivalent resistance of the above circuit is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>180</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p>Current through the circuit is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>90</mn><mn>180</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Reading of the voltmeter is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mi>R</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>400</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39791,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0.001</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Current <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>E</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br />Power generated in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>R</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>for maximum power <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mtext>when,</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mtext>then,&#160;</mtext><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>P</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><img height=\"180\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d0885913-1dae-4d6c-8a1d-7427c5de9c07-image.png\" width=\"271\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39714,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>97</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>110</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>82</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mi>&#8467;</mi><mi>A</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>&#961;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>63</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mfenced><mrow><mn>51</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>97</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39896,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$19.8 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~kg}$","$9.9 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~kg}$","$6.6 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~kg}$","$1.1 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~kg}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{m}=$ Zit,\n$\\mathrm{m}=3.3 \\times 10^{-7} \\times 3 \\times 2=19.8 \\times 10^{-7} \\mathrm{~kg}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":39678,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cd39d40-186d-47ca-8675-89ad2d232b53-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 215px;\" /></p><p>Each pair on the right side of the circuit is in parallel connection, hence it can be replaced by a resistance of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;as shown.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fcb36ad6-95ee-4612-b1f0-8a4972255bc5-image.png\" style=\"width: 310px; height: 148px;\" /></p><p>Now,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;in each branch on the right side is in series, hence combined resistance value will be,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>. Upper branch having resistance&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;is in parallel with another&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>, hence it can be written as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/97933f2e-28b1-4739-8e05-d40f9c15f36b-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 176px;\" /></p><p>Further, simplified circuit will have net resistance of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b88fa5bd-9115-4e56-b160-b41b894b50e0-image.png\" style=\"width: 220px; height: 192px;\" /></p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>eq</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>7</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p>Now, current&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Hence, value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39892,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$1 \\mathrm{~A}$","$2 \\mathrm{~A}$","$4 A$","$6 \\mathrm{~A}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The given circuit can be written as\n$$\n\\mathrm{I}=\\frac{6 \\mathrm{~V}}{1.5 \\Omega}=4 \\mathrm{~A}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null}]